<div id="review_1238822778" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1238822778" />
    <a title="Mark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6755739-mark"><img alt="Mark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1382617992p2/6755739.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1238822778?book_show_action=true">Feb 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark" href="/user/show/6755739-mark">Mark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6755739-mark?shelf=2021">2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6755739-mark?shelf=biography">biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6755739-mark?shelf=historical-novel">historical-novel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1238822778" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13721098355647492557">This book was on my radar for some time but with reading &quot;Das Boot&quot; the ultimate submarine novel albeit from a German perspective and then Alistair Maclean&apos;s book &quot;HMS Ulysses&quot; about the Murmansk convoys this book was mentioned a few times but other readers of this genre. So I finaly took the book and read it.<br/>Like in a previous novel by Erik Larson he does not just tell you the story but also places the story in its historical place. Yes this the story about a great ocean passengership that got </span>
  <span id="freeText13721098355647492557" style="display:none">This book was on my radar for some time but with reading "Das Boot" the ultimate submarine novel albeit from a German perspective and then Alistair Maclean's book "HMS Ulysses" about the Murmansk convoys this book was mentioned a few times but other readers of this genre. So I finaly took the book and read it.<br />Like in a previous novel by Erik Larson he does not just tell you the story but also places the story in its historical place. Yes this the story about a great ocean passengership that got torpedoed by a German submarine in 1915 some miles of the Irish coast and sank pretty quick. <br />Larson paints a picture of the ship, the politics, the passengers, the captain of the submarine, Winston Churchill and his ilk, the US president and he does so pretty efficient.<br />I always was in the understanding that the sinking of the Lusitania was the reason the US entered the first Worldwar, which happened just two years later. What an eye-opener that was. (Now I have to read the Zimmerman Telegram by Barbara Tuchman to add some more knowledge on the decisions around the US entry in the war. <br />It is an fascinating story in which a lot of poor decisions lead to a big shipping disaster only three years after the sinking of the Titanic. This story is just as tragic and the loss of life to big to be forgotten.<br />Larson puts a human face upon the story and makes history a bit more interesting in his writing choices. I would have prefered some extra pictures of the final voyage and of some of the main characters, but that is something personal. And the book is 353 pages long with notes making it a 430 page book, so well researched I migth add.<br /><br />A great novel that deserves to be read about a change in warfare which was initiated by the German Navy, which they did step up in WW2 in cruelty.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13721098355647492557" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


